lay and cut Quick-ſet, trim up your Eſpaliers, and the Hedges of your Paliſadoes; and hitherto you may ſet the Vines, and divers Sorts of Shrubs.

Bring the Orange-trees out of the Conſervatory, at ſuch Times as you ſee the Mulberry-tree put ſorth, and open its Leafs, let the Weather be what it will, for that is an Infallible Rule for the proper Seaſon, to Tranſplant and remove them, but do it with Care, drawing the Tree out with competent Mould ſticking to it, when you have well looſed it from the ſides of the caſe, and ſo with better eaſe place it in another, filled with Earth, taking up the firſt half ſplit, juſt under the Turf of the richeſt Paſture Ground, in a place that has been well fothered, and take rotten Cow-dung one part, and mix with this, or at leaſt very mellow Soil, well skreened or ſifted; and if this proves too ſtiff, ſift a little Loam in it, or a little Lime, with the ſmall rotten Sticks of Willows;
